Case in point... several panelists and participants shared their love for cars and snowmachines. We're not monolithic beings -- we have facets and dimensions and perspectives we can speak from that don't entail always wearing the "environmentalist" or "scientist" hat. 7/

As the ocean warms, it is harder and harder to have cool nights (and days) in a marine-influenced environment. Since water retains heat longer than land, ocean temperatures peak in August, leading to this phenomenon.

Here are nights below 60Àö in August. They used to be common. Even in the mid 2000s, we averaged 4 per August. Now they are quite rare: we've averaged 1 per month in the past 13 years.[FWIW, the reporting site changed from Downtown to Logan in 1936] https://t.co/l8Zpq4l6N7

Temperatures in the 50s used to be frequent in all parts of August.We haven't had a temperature below 59Àö before August 26 since 2008.Want to see a hockey stick? Here is a hockey stick! https://t.co/iXFG8njmPo
From 1872 to 1995, there were only three times a 58Àö temperature was not recorded in August (2.4%).Since then, there have been 11 Augusts with temperatures entirely above 58Àö (42.3%).

Last year was an outlier: it didn't fall below 59Àö until the 20th! That was 5 days later than the previous record (2016). Last September was the second warmest on record. But is September 2 early for cooler temperatures? Not at all.

Recent work finds that industrial decline can drive advantaged groups to look inward and defend existing political hierarchies. This article suggests that for other groups, the impetus may rather be to seek new levels of political voice denied under that status quo.

Using census records linked over time, I find that ethnic concentration in growing mines suppressed immigrants‚Äô pursuit of citizenship and the right to vote. But this constraint broke down as mines declined, especially where the potential returns to enfranchisement were greatest.

Immigrants inhabited dense ethnic enclaves in coal communities, relying on institutions like fraternal insurance associations and ethnic congregations to weather frequent ebbs in industrial activity and shocks like injuries in the mines. https://t.co/Hlx86YW4Hn

To test this theory, I look to the U.S. coal industry in the early 20th century‚Äîa volatile industry in a volatile global economy. Coal was then one of the most diverse industries in country, employing many thousands of immigrants from Southern and Eastern Europe. https://t.co/vyKfmtPQ7C

When the industry declines, however, that concentration amplifies losses within the group, casting doubt on its ability to manage economic risk. This prompts people to look beyond coethnics for more reliable, durable support‚Äîsuch as that promised by political enfranchisement.

I argue that when a group is concentrated in a steadily growing industry, members become more confident in coethnics‚Äô ability to support their welfare absent help from the state, such as via ethnic mutual aid societies.

Ethnic groups often concentrate in specific industries. I ask how this clustering affects politically excluded groups (specifically migrant groups), which are often segmented into the workforces of highly volatile industries, in times of growth and decline.

@sandypsj A lot of the federal government has settled into a model where the federal employees manage contracts and the contractors have most of the expertise. A very bad model, but so engrained into the federal bureaucracy that it's hard to shake off.
Full disclosure: my partner works on a consulting contract to FEMA, though not on disaster relief.

And clearly, consultants are not the *villains* here; many of them are true experts, sometimes more so than bureaucrats who might care more about process than outcomes (a real thing! Sometimes exaggerated! But real!).

Some of this is inevitable and necessary; given the unpredictable nature of disasters, if FEMA tried to handle it all internally, it would be alternatingly accused of overstaffing and not having the resources to handle what it needs to do.

...and curbing rampant consumption at home without outsourcing carbon dumps to poorer countries.Window-dressing at this stage is a collective joke at our own expense. Unchecked privilege in your commentary is either blatant ignorance or intellectual dishonesty.

The governments of the Global North may do well not to capitulate to private sector oligarchies and focus on slashing emissions, investing in renewable energy, transferring this technology to the Global South, paying reparations via the Green Climate Fund,...

It is always the prerogative of the powerful to pretend asymmetry doesn't exist. The path forward cannot be built on ignoring these asymmetries, but through fully acknowledging them and rooting every analysis in them.Anything else is not just embarrassing, but dangerous.
The Global North can refocus energies away from policing the legitimate outrage and demands for accountability coming from the South ‚Äî especially at a time of colossal tragedy.

There is no smart, roundabout way around this which can make everyone profit while we‚Äôre at it. Funds ‚Äì public, private, bilateral, multilateral, hybrid ‚Äì must be funnelled towards this end, and directly so.

Add to this the labyrinth of calculating emissions and we‚Äôre soon lost in a web of convenient definitions, jargon, well-meaning technological fixes, and conflicts of interest.The solution is as simple as it is complex: carbon emissions must reduce in absolute terms.
This top-down approach comes with increased climate injustices, land-use change, and a full circle of emission ‚Äúcertification‚Äù which defers and deflects issues rather than address them.

The idea that the free market can be used to initiate this bigger shift when it is at the root of the issue is, frankly, absurd. Concepts such as the ‚Äúcarbon market‚Äù merely greenwash emissions and result in the commodification of the environment, while achieving very little.

This lack of imagination on part of the most ‚Äúdeveloped‚Äù countries is astounding. Climate change is a structural problem requiring long-term, permanent, structural solutions.And this cannot be achieved by white-washing the sins of colonialism, imperialism and capitalism.

The capitalist worldview of how to ‚Äúresolve‚Äù the climate crisis is taken for granted as the norm and all critical approaches lumped together as other, radical theories. Or, worse, they're seen as a deliberate attempt by the less powerful to ‚Äúother‚Äù themselves.

The issue of climate financing is so inherently political and the present international structures that determine it so entirely dominated by Western economic thought, that the default approach to such questions is steeped in neoliberal ideology.

I may not receive comments on this thread - fine. I may receive flack from my fellow climate change activists who feel activism should extend to teachers in the classroom. I am sorry but that is really not the right thing to do for my learners some of whom may self-harm. There.
...Our young people deserve the facts and knowledge we give them in their education, the vulnerable deserve to be protected. They all deserve hope.

...I would be doing them harm if I turned away from this disassociation. I hope that the potential careers in ICT and Business that I so carefully diagrammed on my classroom wall yesterday still exist for them in the future...

I disassociate my teaching from my concern. Even during the climate discussions in Business and in science, I stick to the facts and do not preach. Why? Because these kids are vulnerable, they do not have the emotional resources to cope with doomer messages...

...With Business, again I stick to the curriculum for the qual they aim at. That includes business ethics which includes climate change. We discuss it. So I'm teaching  aspects of climate change, but only within the bounds of their curriculum. I stick to that & to the facts...

...but do not aim to frighten the students - I stick to the science and am not a one trick pony. Did I mention we get a lot of kids who have anxiety disorder? I make the science light and happy. We do everything; chem, phys, biol and develop critical thinking skills...

...I teach the science with experiments and practicals - all the fun bits, as it is an enrichment lesson not a GCSE and my prev. job was running science clubs doing this.  Of course, I introduce the Greenhouse effect and talk about climate change where it is relevant...

...they deserve the possibility of a "normal" future. So here is my approach. I teach the maths - all fine. I use an active, storyline and game-based approach and try to get the learners totally absorbed into the lesson...

...but those kids deserve their chance for a qualification. The faculty I work in is specifically for learners with high needs or challenges to learning like ASD, family issues, behaviour issues or kids who have so far been home educated and want to come to college...

So I could just give up teaching, join XR and become an activist. That's an option, though I have kids and need to work to help pay the bills. Or I could compromise my position and spout off about climate change through my (GCSE Maths, Science, IT, Business) lessons...

@archaeostef Can I throw something into the mix? When we think of architecture we imagine bare stone or brick (generalisation). We know that water, temp, & salt decay. We also know that the bare stone paradigm is a 19th c dream. If we reconsidered architecture as coated knowing it moderates

Marijana Lukacevic is demonstrating to us the impact of climate change on populations in medieval Croatia and how this comes across on the archaeological remains i.e. the presence of cribrae orbitaliae indicates childhood nutritional deficiency, caused by lower agriculture yields

Climatic fluctuations had major impacts.  So water management and security absolutely crucial. Infrastructure such as Qanats provided water supplies to cities and were maintained, but also targeted during military action. Was the climate a driver for the formation of such cities?

After another discussion break @PeterBrown___ on water management in medieval middle-eastern cities. Baghdad est. pop ca. 280k-500k at its peak, enormous compared to medieval European cities. Water required for everyday life and agriculture, but climate not exactly conducive

@eva_svensson Jo Mckenzie @bradarcforensic is demonstrating to us the worth of geoarchaeological techniques for being able to understand the 'Broo' community on Shetland which survived sandblow events in c14th & c16th by adaptation but the area became a vast, permanent dunefield in c17th

After a short discussion on the first three papers @eva_svensson is starting things off again by taking us through the strategies carried out by med. peasants in boreal inland Scandinavia to mitigate against cc. - cultivation of oats, adapting houses to withstand colder climate

Next up is @samuel_p_johns presenting on the very interesting @ercb2c project which developed non-destructive method for sampling of animal lipids from medieval manuscripts to reconstruct precipitation driven climate records through the stable isotope composition.Fascinating!

The second paper is from @Booleying @BenjaminGearey @Kevin_M_Kearney who are looking at pollen records to examine how pastoral regions in Highland Scotland and Ireland fared in the early and mid 'Little Ice Age'
